******
[1] Thailand
Date: Mon 28 Apr 2008
Source: China View, Xinhua News Agency report [edited]
<http://news.xinhuanet.com/english/2008-04/28/content_8068292.htm>


Thailand's Public Health Ministry warned the public to be alert
regarding dengue fever prevention measures as [12] patients died and
over 10 000 have suffered from the disease during the 1st quarter of
2008, according to Chaiya Sasomsub, minister of public health, on
Monday [28 Apr 2008].

From [1 Jan 2008] to [19 Apr 2008], the cumulative number of dengue
fever patients soared to 10 901 and 99 percent of the patients were
completely recovered, Chaiya said. However, 12 patients in the
country have been killed by dengue fever this year [2008], he said.

"When compared with the same period last year [2007], the number of
dengue fever patients has increased by 80 percent," the minister was
quoted by local news network The Nation as saying.

Chaiya said he had instructed local health officials nationwide to
maintain the campaign to eradicate the mosquito breeding habitats.

[Editor: Pliny Han]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur Brent Barrett

[While the above report does not mention geographic distribution of
cases within Thailand, this information is available as spreadsheets
that can be downloaded from the Thai Ministry of Public Health
disease surveillance website. While the disease specific pages are
written in Thai, using the links to 2551 and 2550 will provide data
on cases by geographic distribution by province for the years 2008
and 2007 respectively. Data on dengue fever are available at
<http://203.157.15.4/surdata/disease.php?ds=66>; data on dengue
hemorrhagic fever (DHF) are available at
<http://203.157.15.4/surdata/disease.php?ds=26>; and data on dengue
shock syndrome (DSS) are available at
<http://203.157.15.4/surdata/disease.php?ds=27>.

The HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map of Thailand can be accessed
at <http://healthmap.org/promed?v=15.1,101,5>. - Mods.TY/MPP]

******
[2] Malaysia
Date: Sun 27 Apr 2008
Source: Malaysia Star [edited]
<http://thestar.com.my/news/story.asp?file=/2008/4/27/nation/20080427080828&sec=nation>



In the 1st 3 months of the year [2008], 5 municipal councils have
been singled out as hotspots for dengue fever. They are Shah Alam
(719 cases), Klang (582), Johor Baru (536), Kajang (514), and Subang
Jaya (457).

Health minister Datuk Liow Tiong Lai said: "It looks quite serious in
the Klang Valley."

Liow also revealed that Selangor topped the list for dengue fever
with 3742 cases. It was followed by Kuala Lumpur (1119 cases) and
Perak (1084 cases).

"We can prevent this. But we need the cooperation and support of the
public besides cooperation of agencies especially local councils to
come forward and work with the ministry. Then, we should be able to
reduce the number of dengue fever cases." There has been a 29 percent
decline this year [2008] compared to the period between [1 Jan and 31
Mar 2007], which saw 34 deaths. So far, 25 people have died.

Disease Control Division director Datuk Dr Hasan Abdul Rahman in a
press statement posted on the ministry's website said there were 776
dengue cases with one death reported from 13-16 Apr [2008]. This was
an increase of 35 cases from the week before.

It had been reported that an immediate stop work order was carried
out on 25 construction sites in the Klang Valley by the Selangor
Health Department for failing to keep the areas free from the _Aedes_ mosquito.

[Byline: Audrey Edwards]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail Rapporteur A-Lan Banks

