[3] Reunion Island
Date: Thu 24 Apr 2008
Source: Institut de Veille Sanitaire, Point Epidemiologique
Hebdomadaire Sur la Dengue a la Reunion [in French, trans. & summ.
Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.invs.sante.fr/presse/2008/le_point_sur/dengue_pep_reunion_250408/pehdengue_sem17.pdf>



In April 2008, 2 cases of dengue confirmed in residents of Rivier St.
Louis, commune of Saint Louis, were reported to the department of
healthcare of the Reunion Regional Directorate for Health and Social
Affairs (DRASS). A reinforcement of the epidemiological surveillance
was then proposed by the interregional epidemiological department of
Reunion and Mayotte (CIRE RM) in conjunction with the integrated
[pest management] actions of the teams from DRASS's Reinforced
Prophylaxis Service.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[Although 2 dengue cases can hardly be classified as an outbreak, the
severe chikungunya virus epidemic in Reunion and other Indian Ocean
islands in 2005-2006 indicates that a population of _Aedes_ vector
mosquitoes is likely still prevalent there, and if so, could spark a
significant dengue outbreak.

A map of Reunion Island can be accessed at
<http://www.maplandia.com/reunion/>. - Mod.TY]

******
[4] Brazil (Rio Grande do Norte)
Date: Fri 18 Apr 2008
Source: Terra [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://noticias.terra.com.br/brasil/interna/0,,OI2756309-EI715,00.html>


The Rio Grande do Norte is in a state of maximum health alert. The
number of cases of dengue hemorrhagic fever (DHF) increased by 1000
percent over the same period last year [2007]. There are now 453
cases of DHF, with 21 deaths. "The situation is very serious. We
currently have 15 municipalities with a dengue epidemic," highlighted
the state secretary of health, Adelmaro Cavalcanti.

The problem of dengue is not confined only to DHF. The number of
notifications of classic [dengue] cases grew 200 percent over the
same period last year [2007], reaching 12 317 cases. The situation is
worse in the region of the Grande Natal, which reported half of the
cases throughout state. The city of Natal decreed a state of
emergency due to the dengue epidemic.

The concern is that the number of victims in Rio Grande do Norte is
even greater than that recorded. The State Health Department admits
that there is underreporting where the doctors and the urgent aid
network of state hospitals are not filling out the notification forms
for suspected cases of the disease. "Since the beginning of the year
[2008], this has been the great struggle of the registry with the
unit's hospitals throughout the state and also is the main topic in
meetings with the municipal [health] secretaries," Cavalcanti said.

[Byline: Anna Ruth]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed@promedmail.org>

[A map showing the states in Brazil can be accessed at
