******
[5] Brazil (Bahia)
Date: Mon 21 Apr 2008
Source: Parana-Online [in Portuguese, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.parana-online.com.br/noticias/index.php?op=ver&id=342893&caderno=3>


The heavy rainfall recorded in the west and the north of Bahia since
the beginning of the year [2008] -- pronounced since the 1st week of
March [2008] -- is of concern to those responsible for public health
of Bahia, who fear an even greater increase in cases of dengue in the
state. In the 1st quarter of year [2008], 12 607 cases of the disease
were recorded, 80 percent more than in same period of 2007. In
Presidente Dutra, in the Irece region 474 km (295 mi) west of
Salvador, for example, a [dengue] epidemic hit a population of 14
000: 2440 contracted the disease this year [2008].

As a reaction, at the end of last week [week of 14 Apr 2008] the
government Bahia inaugurated the state committee to combat dengue,
which brought together the Bahia Secretariat of Health (Sesab),
municipalities and non-governmental organizations. Together, they
launched the campaign "Everyone Against Dengue," the main goal of
which is public awareness of the importance of combating the breeding
of _Aedes aegypti_ mosquitoes, the transmitter of the virus causing
the disease.

For [state] Governor Jaques Wagner, this is the only measure to
contain the advance of dengue. "All the measures that the government
can do will not stop the cycle of disease," he said. To achieve this
goal, this week the government will run advertising on TV, radio, and
newspapers, with tips on how eliminate breeding foci of the mosquito.
Furthermore, [educational] activities will be held in schools, with
the participation of students." Students are multipliers, which take
what they learn at school into the home, " indicated the secretary of
health, Jorge Solla.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-PORT
<promed@promedmail.org>

