[6] Brazil (Rio de Janeiro)
Date: Tue 22 Apr 2008
Source: Globo On Line, Reuters report [in Portuguese, trans. & summ.
Mod. TY, edited]
<http://oglobo.globo.com/pais/mat/2008/04/22/dengue_causa_92_mortes_no_rio_epidemia_a_pior_ja_registrada-427006757.asp>


The epidemic of dengue has killed 92 people in Rio de Janeiro in
2008, the largest number of deaths resulting from the disease now
officially registered in the State.

This Tuesday [22 Apr 2008] the State Secretariat of Health announced
that 110 783 people were infected [with dengue virus] this year
[2008]. In addition to the 92 confirmed deaths, another 96 [suspected
dengue cases] are still under investigation as possibly related to
the epidemic.

In less than 4 months, the current epidemic surpassed the 91 deaths
from dengue in 2002, when over 288 000 cases of the disease were
recorded in the State throughout that [entire] year. This time the
proportional fatality of disease is much improved.

More than half of the victims of the [dengue virus] transmitted by
the vector mosquito _ Aedes aegypti _ were in the state capital,
where 56 919 people were infected and 55 died.

About half the dead in the state were less than 15 years [old].
According to experts, the children are more susceptible because they
have not had previous contact with type 2 disease [dengue virus],
which predominates in current epidemic.

The latest weekly report released by the [case] registry shows an
increase of 5 deaths and nearly 18 000 recorded cases recorded in
relation to the previous [weekly] period.

After the capital, the counties hardest hit by the dengue epidemic of
dengue are Duque de Caxias (11 deaths), Sao Joao de Meriti (5), and
Angra dos Reis (4).

Throughout the past year [2007], 66 553 people contracted dengue
[virus infections] in the State of Rio, with 31 deaths. In the
capital, the 56 919 cases this year [2008] far outweigh the 25 107
[dengue cases] last year [2007], when 26 people died in the entire year.

The state health secretary, Sergio Cortes, said last week [week of 14
Apr 2008] that Rio was still "at the apex of the epidemic" and
dismissed [previous reports] that there was a reduction in the number
of cases due to fewer people in queues at hospitals and health posts.

According to him, care was better organized after the adoption of
emergency measures, such as armed forces field hospitals and
rehydration stations for patients.

State authorities expect that, beyond such measures, the fall of
temperature in the coming weeks, after a hot and humid summer, will
help to contain the epidemic.

In 2002, cases fell sharply from April [onward]. While March had 99
861 cases reported, in April the number fell to 31 642, and in May
there were 7208 [cases].

[Byline: Pedro Fonseca]

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[A report published in La Nacion
<http://www.lanacion.com.py/noticias_um.php?not=184581> indicated
that the official number of dengue deaths in Rio state reached 95,
with 58 in the city, commenting that the actual number may be higher
due to underreporting. - Mod.TY

The outbreaks discussed in this update can also be found on the
HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at
<http://www.healthmap.org/promed>. - CopyEd.MJ]
